So my wife came home and said her job, which already won't get her off closing shifts, is talking about making her do split shifts. So going in to open, getting a few hours in the middle of the day off, then coming back in to close. I got very angry and said that was BS and unfair and all kinds of stuff and her response was "why is it your problem?" Am I crazy here? Does my wife's work hours not count as my problem at least in some capacity?

Yes it is your problem to an extent, but also you only have to tangentially deal with it. It's sweet., and she should appreciate that you care about her situation to be upset with it, but if she is fine with it, they that's kinda it, y'know? As long as it isn't impacting anything super serious on your day to day life. If it is, in that case there should obviously be a discussion about it.

Sure, but she's not fine with it. She's not as angry as I am, but she's been miserable in general with her job recently due to the fact that they promoted her, gave her a really difficult area with less experience than the other promoted person, twice as much work and still won't get her off closings, which she's been asking for since last year

Then I think her reaction may just be from her being frustrated as well, and kind of venting since you're obviously just as upset as she is. It could have obviously been done in a less aggressive manner, but I don't think it was meant as anything rude or malicious. You both have very valid points.

There’s little you can do, too; when I’m in the middle of a shitty situation at work and one of my other coworkers, who cannot help, decides to complain too, it grates on me. I imagine the effect is similar here. Misery does not love company
Fair points, to both of you. I just hate the idea of people taking advantage of her. She works her ass off for this place and already gets very little time with her family as is
I can get behind this.
